{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609148"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:44:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16091"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.14,0.03,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67241"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52693"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1779"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9658"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22494"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67241"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents at 34 weeks gestation with vaginal bleeding. Her obstetric history includes two previous caesarean sections. Ultrasound shows an anterior placenta praevia. During attempted delivery, severe haemorrhage occurs when removing the placenta. Emergency hysterectomy is performed due to uncontrolled bleeding. Pathological examination of the placenta and uterus shows loss of decidua and deep invasion of chorionic villi into the myometrium at the placental insertion site. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placenta accreta","Complete placental abruption","Partial placental abruption","Gestational trophoblastic disease","Vasa praevia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta accreta\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when placental tissue abnormally invades the myometrium. Risk factors include previous caesarean section, placenta praevia, and other uterine surgery. The abnormal invasion prevents normal placental separation after delivery, leading to severe haemorrhage that often requires hysterectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E involve premature separation of a normally implanted placenta, not abnormal invasion. \u003Cstrong\u003EGestational trophoblastic disease\u003C/strong\u003E involves abnormal proliferation of placental tissue but does not typically present with this clinical picture. \u003Cstrong\u003EVasa praevia\u003C/strong\u003E involves fetal vessels running through the membranes over the cervical os, which can rupture causing fetal haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of previous caesarean sections, placenta praevia, and severe haemorrhage requiring hysterectomy is classic for placenta accreta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placenta accreta occurs when placental tissue invades abnormally deeply into the myometrium, often at sites of previous uterine scarring.","Risk factors for placenta accreta include previous caesarean 